name: 1,4,7,10-tetraoxacyclododecane
Reason: The basic unit of 1,4,7,10-tetraoxacyclododecane is ethylene oxide, which has a melting point of -111.3 °C. The addition of multiple ethylene oxide units to form a 12-membered ring (1,4,7,10-tetraoxacyclododecane) increases the strain on the molecule, reducing the tendency to pack in a solid form, thus raising the melting point. Crown ethers, which have a similar structure, have melting points that range widely, with 18-crown-6, a compound with a very similar structure, melting at around 38 °C. However, the smaller ring size of the 12-membered ring in 1,4,7,10-tetraoxacyclododecane should result in a lower melting point compared to the 18-crown-6 due to increased ring strain. Considering these factors and the empirical data on similar compounds, the melting point of 1,4,7,10-tetraoxacyclododecane is expected to be significantly higher than the monomer but lower than larger crown ethers.
